Goal is to assign counties to one of nine congressional districts.¶

Considerations:¶
  • C1: Equal populations with no more or no less than 30% of the average population difference (arbritrary cut-off; Average population was determined to be the [total population/9])
  • C2: Each county can be assigned to one district only
  • C3: Counties with populations >760,000 are assigned to their own district
  • C4: None of the districts may be more than 95% white-only
  • C5: Districts should be comprised of adjacent counties
    • Notes about constraint exploration:¶
  • C1: Satisfied
  • C2: Satisfied
  • C3: Not possible; Results in infeasible solution
  • C4: Not possible; Due to state demographics (racial composition; heavily white-only), this results in an infeasible solution. The constraint was relaxed to as low as 80% white-only and it was still infeasible.
  • C5: Unable to integrate a solution for this constraint due to insufficient computational resources.

# Initialize the problem
prob = pulp.LpProblem("CountyAssignment", pulp.LpMinimize)

# Decision variables
# Assignments of counties to groups (binary variables)
assign = pulp.LpVariable.dicts("Assign", ((county, group) for county in county_data for group in range(1, 10)), cat='Binary')

# Objective function:
prob += pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] for county in county_data for group in range(1, 10))

# Constraints
# Constraint 1: Equal populations with no more or no less than 30% of the average population
average_population = total_population / 9
for group in range(1, 10):
    prob += (
        pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data) >= 0.70 * average_population
    )
    prob += (
        pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data) <= 1.30 * average_population
    )
    
    
# Constraint 1 ALTERNATE:  Equal populations with no more or no less than 5% of a total population difference
#total_population = sum(data['population'] for data in county_data.values())
#max_diff = total_population * 0.05
#for group in range(1, 10):
#    prob += (pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data) >= total_population/9 - max_diff)
#    prob += (pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data) <= total_population/9 + max_diff)

# Constraint 2: Each county can only be assigned to one group
for county in county_data:
    prob += (pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] for group in range(1, 10)) == 1)

# Constraint 3: If population > 761,000 then assign the county to its own group
#for county in county_data:
#   if county_data[county]['population'] > 400000:
#        for group in range(1, 10):
#            prob += (assign[county, group] == 0)
#        prob += (assign[county, group] == 1)

# Constraint 3 ALTERNATE: Assign 'County59' to its own group (group 10)
#for group in range(1, 10):
#    prob += (assign['County59', group] == 0)  # Ensure 'County59' is not assigned to any other group
#    if group == 10:
#        prob += (assign['County59', group] == 1)  # Assign 'County59' to group 10

# Constraint 4: None of the nine groups can be over 95% white
#for group in range(1, 10):
#    white_population_ratio = sum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['white'] / county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data)
#    prob += white_population_ratio <= 0.99

# Solve the problem
prob.solve()

# Output results
print("Status:", pulp.LpStatus[prob.status])
print("Number of counties used:", int(pulp.value(prob.objective)))
for county in county_data:
    for group in range(1, 10):
        if pulp.value(assign[county, group]) == 1:
            print(f"{county} assigned to group {group}")

    from pyproj import Geod

# Initialize Geod object
geod = Geod(ellps="WGS84")

# Function to calculate distance between two points
def calculate_distance(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    _, _, distance = geod.inv(lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2)
    return distance

# Iterate over each pair of counties and calculate distance
for county1_key, county1_data in county_data.items():
    for county2_key, county2_data in county_data.items():
        if county1_key != county2_key:  # Avoid calculating distance between the same county
            distance = calculate_distance(county1_data['latitude'], county1_data['longitude'], county2_data['latitude'], county2_data['longitude'])
            print(f"Distance between {county1_data['county_name']} and {county2_data['county_name']}: {distance} meters")

# Initialize the problem
prob = pulp.LpProblem("CountyAssignment", pulp.LpMinimize)

# Decision variables
# Assignments of counties to groups (binary variables)
assign = pulp.LpVariable.dicts("Assign", ((county, group) for county in county_data for group in range(1, 10)), cat='Binary')

# Objective function: minimize the number of groups used
prob += pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] for county in county_data for group in range(1, 10))

# Constraints
# Constraint 1: Equal populations with no more or no less than 5% of a total population difference
total_population = sum(data['population'] for data in county_data.values())
max_diff = total_population * 0.05
for group in range(1, 10):
    prob += (pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data) >= total_population/9 - max_diff)
    prob += (pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] * county_data[county]['population'] for county in county_data) <= total_population/9 + max_diff)

# Constraint 2: Each county can only be assigned to one group
for county in county_data:
    prob += (pulp.lpSum(assign[county, group] for group in range(1, 10)) == 1)

# Constraint 3: If population > 761,000 then assign the county to its own group
